step.context:
\text{If $ A = [a_{ij}]_{m \times n}$ and } B = [b_{ij}]_{m \times n} 
\text{ are any two matrices,}\\
\text{then, are all the following conclusions correct?}

\text{Are following caclulations and conclusion correct?}\\
\text{Given, } 
2X+3Y = 
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
 2 & 3 \\ 
 4 & 0 \end{array} \right] \\ \text{ and }

 3X+2Y = 
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
 2 & -2 \\ 
 -1 & 5 \end{array} \right]

step.reason:
P_{m \times n} + Q_{m \times n} = S_{m \times n} = [s_{ij}]_{m \times n}\text{ where,}\\
s_{ij} = p_{ij} + q_{ij} \, (\forall \text{ possible ij values)}. \\
\text{Also, if } X = [x_{ij}]_{\,m\times n} \text{ and k is a scalar then,}\\
\text{kX is another matrix of order m\times n}\\
\text{such that }
kX = [k(x_{ij})]_{\,m\times n}

